{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c8e659e4-1dc1-4410-bfbd-95a09f7450c8","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n### 1. Exec into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present)\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find your process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect the trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### Getting the file off the pod\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-nettrace> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### Alternative: use `dotnet-counters` first for a quick look\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-counters\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\n\n> **Tip:** If `dotnet tool install` fails (no SDK in the container), copy the tool binaries in via `kubectl cp`, or use the [EventPipe environment variables](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/eventpipe#trace-using-environment-variables) (`DOTNET_EnableEventPipe=1`) which require no tooling—just a container restart.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"71663242-7dd5-44da-ab04-9f69f137b449","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a troubleshooting/knowledge question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise, actionable steps.","outputTokens":439,"requestId":"D833:FD676:7FB6C0:9377A8:69FBE9D3"},"id":"22918262-2477-4696-8cab-d92df78ce3f5","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:24:47.569Z","parentId":"794fc8ab-004d-48bb-9b11-a49612655f97"}
